ce:section.ce:para:
The synthesis procedure is schematized in Fig. 1
                     . Firstly multi-walled carbon nanotubes were oxidized by sulphuric and nitric acid mixture with the aid of ultrasonication for 6 h at 40 °C. Afterwards the GQD were isolated by adding cysteamine on the CNTs suspension. After the mixing, black carbon nanotubes slowly precipitate and the oxidized GQD in the supernatant, were collected. Finally dicyclohexylcarbodiimide was added to start the coupling reaction and the resulting thiol-functionalized GQD were purified and isolated. By washing the CNTs precipitate several time with DMF is possible to increase the amount of thio-GQD isolated from the CNT. In this way, a complete purification of the CNTs can be obtained. The mass fraction of ox-GQD isolated from the oxidized carbon nanotubes is around 7–9%. The remaining CNTs precipitate does not show any luminescence emission. It is known from the literature that the presence of carboxylated carbonaceous fragments can hamper the sidewall functionalization of the CNTs [21] and this is a crucial point especially for biological applications. The reason of the detachment of the GQD induced by the presence of cysteamine is unknown and cannot be ascribed to the pH change of the solution due to the aminic group of the cysteamine. Tests of stability of the oxidized carbon nanotubes at basic pH by using different bases (ammonia or NaOH) do not lead to any change of the solution stability even at high pH value (12–13). Our hypothesis is that cysteamine acts as an exfoliation agent causing the detachment of nano-graphene fragments produced by the oxidation reaction. It is likely that these fragments are linked to the CNTs backbone through π–π stacking interaction. Intercalation of small molecules of cysteamine between the GQD and the CNT sidewall could reduce the π–π coupling causing the detachment of the GQD. The high oxidation of the carbon nanotubes can also play a role in the detachment of the GQD from the CNTs surface. The thio-GQD were found to form stable colloidal suspensions in various solvents including ethanol and dimethylformamide. Nonetheless, the water solubility of the thio-GQD is lower than that of the ox-GQD. This could limit the application of thio-GQD as fluorescent markers for biological applications. From the UV–vis absorption in DMF (Fig. 1), an absorption peak at around 390 nm was observed as likewise reported for some carbon dots spectra [22]. Photoluminescence (PL) measurements in the 400–750 nm with different excitation wavelength show an intense excitation-dependent PL emission. The spectrum reported in Fig. 1 (bottom right) shows the luminescence of the thio-GQD obtained with different excitation wavelength. Using quinine sulphate as a reference (QY = 0.54) [23], the PL quantum yield in DMF was measured to be around 0.107, which is in agreement with other results reported in literature for luminescent graphene carbon dots [24,25] but lower respect to that reported recently by Shen et al. [26]. In addition, thio-GQD exhibit an excitation- and solvent-dependent PL behavior. By excitation from 380 to 560 nm, the PL peak shifts of around 160 nm and its intensity decreases following an exponential trend (Fig. 1). This excitation-dependent PL behavior was extensively reported in fluorescent carbon-based nanomaterials and it may be explained by the inhomogeneities of the orbital energy distribution of the defects states [6]. The PL lineshape does not vary upon the solvent used (DMF or ethanol). On the opposite, the QY of the thio-GQD in DMF was found to be higher than in ethanol. In particular the estimated QY in ethanol is approximately one half of that obtained in DMF. This solvent dependency of the emission efficiency may be due to a better solubilization of the thio-GQD in DMF and consequently reduction of the self-quenching phenomena. The nano-graphene displays a visible luminescence induced by the presence of defects and/or functional groups in the sample introduced by the passivation of the functional groups as revealed also by the XPS analysis (see Fig. 2
                     ). In ox-GQD the C1s core line presents a high number of carbon–oxygen bonds, like carboxyl (288.81 eV), hydroxyl and ether-like bonds (286.45 eV) similar to results described in literature [27]. The presence of a high amount of oxygen-containing defects in ox-GQD is confirmed also by Raman spectroscopy (Fig. S1a). Two classical features are present in the spectrum of ox-GQD assigned to D mode (1330 cm−1) and G mode (1582 cm−1).
